Before one agent can delegate to another, it has to *discover* what the other can do. A2A standardizes this as the Agent Card — the agent equivalent of an OpenAPI spec.

```typescript
interface Skill {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  inputModes: string[];
  outputModes: string[];
}
interface AgentCard {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  url: string;
  skills: Skill[];
}

function buildAgentCard(): AgentCard {
  return {
    name: "translator-agent",
    description: "Translates text between languages",
    url: "https://agents.example.com/translator",
    skills: [
      { id: "translate", name: "translate",
        inputModes: ["text/plain"], outputModes: ["text/plain"] },
    ],
  };
}

function findSkill(card: AgentCard, capability: string): Skill | undefined {
  return card.skills.find(s => s.id === capability || s.name === capability);
}

const card = buildAgentCard();
const skill = findSkill(card, "translate");
console.log(skill ? `can do: ${skill.name} @ ${card.url}` : "capability not found");
```

Output:

```
can do: translate @ https://agents.example.com/translator
```

**Why discovery is a protocol concern.** Without a standard card format, every agent-to-agent integration is bespoke: the caller must know in advance what the callee can do and how to talk to it. The Agent Card makes capability *self-describing* and *queryable* — a calling agent fetches the card, checks `skills` for what it needs (including the input/output modes it can actually produce and consume), and only then delegates. This is the discovery layer that turns N² custom integrations into a uniform lookup, and it is the direct descendant of FIPA's agent directory (Lesson 02). The next exercise builds the actual delegation call on top of this discovery.

MCP standardizes how an agent uses external tools: the server *advertises* tool schemas, the agent *discovers* them, and invocation is validated against the schema. This is the vertical complement to A2A's horizontal agent-to-agent calls.

```typescript
type ToolImpl = (args: Record<string, unknown>) => unknown;
interface Tool { schema: { required: string[] }; impl: ToolImpl; }

class MCPServer {
  private tools = new Map<string, Tool>();
  register(name: string, schema: { required: string[] }, impl: ToolImpl) {
    this.tools.set(name, { schema, impl });
  }
  listTools() {
    return [...this.tools].map(([name, t]) => ({ name, required: t.schema.required }));
  }
  callTool(name: string, args: Record<string, unknown>) {
    const t = this.tools.get(name);
    if (!t) throw new Error(`no such tool: ${name}`);
    return t.impl(args);
  }
}

function useTool(server: MCPServer, name: string, args: Record<string, unknown>) {
  const spec = server.listTools().find(t => t.name === name);
  if (!spec) return { ok: false, error: "tool not advertised" };
  const missing = spec.required.filter(r => !(r in args));   // validate FIRST
  if (missing.length) return { ok: false, error: `missing args: ${missing.join(",")}` };
  return { ok: true, result: server.callTool(name, args) };
}

const server = new MCPServer();
server.register("weather", { required: ["city"] },
  (a) => `sunny in ${a.city}`);

console.log(useTool(server, "weather", { city: "Berlin" }));   // ok
console.log(useTool(server, "weather", {}));                    // rejected early
```

Output:

```
{ ok: true, result: 'sunny in Berlin' }
{ ok: false, error: 'missing args: city' }
```

**Discovery + validation is the protocol's value.** The agent does not hardcode knowledge of the `weather` tool — it calls `listTools()` to discover the schema, then validates its arguments against the advertised `required` list *before* invoking. The invalid call is rejected at the agent boundary, never reaching the implementation. This separation (advertise → discover → validate → invoke) is what makes tools swappable: any MCP server exposing a `weather` tool with a `city` arg is a drop-in replacement, and the agent's validation logic is uniform across all tools. Every major 2026 framework ships MCP support precisely because this uniformity eliminates per-tool integration code.

The protocols are not competitors — they are layers solving different problems. The production skill is recognizing which problem(s) a request poses and composing the right layers.

```typescript
interface Request {
  needsTool: boolean;
  needsAnotherAgent: boolean;
  regulatedAuditTrail: boolean;
  crossUntrustedOrgs: boolean;
}

function routeProtocol(r: Request): { protocols: string[]; why: string[] } {
  const protocols: string[] = [];
  const why: string[] = [];
  if (r.needsTool) { protocols.push("MCP"); why.push("MCP: vertical agent<->tool access"); }
  if (r.needsAnotherAgent) { protocols.push("A2A"); why.push("A2A: horizontal agent<->agent delegation"); }
  if (r.regulatedAuditTrail) { protocols.push("ACP"); why.push("ACP: enterprise audit / compliance trail"); }
  if (r.crossUntrustedOrgs) { protocols.push("ANP"); why.push("ANP: decentralized trust across untrusted parties"); }
  return { protocols, why };
}

const requests: [string, Request][] = [
  ["look up the weather", { needsTool: true, needsAnotherAgent: false, regulatedAuditTrail: false, crossUntrustedOrgs: false }],
  ["delegate research to a peer agent that searches the web",
   { needsTool: true, needsAnotherAgent: true, regulatedAuditTrail: false, crossUntrustedOrgs: false }],
  ["process a regulated insurance claim",
   { needsTool: true, needsAnotherAgent: true, regulatedAuditTrail: true, crossUntrustedOrgs: false }],
  ["buy compute from an unknown third-party agent",
   { needsTool: false, needsAnotherAgent: true, regulatedAuditTrail: false, crossUntrustedOrgs: true }],
];
for (const [name, r] of requests) {
  const { protocols } = routeProtocol(r);
  console.log(`${name.padEnd(50)} -> ${protocols.join(" + ")}`);
}
```

Output:

```
look up the weather                                -> MCP
delegate research to a peer agent that searches the web -> MCP + A2A
process a regulated insurance claim                -> MCP + A2A + ACP
buy compute from an unknown third-party agent      -> A2A + ANP
```

**Why production pairs protocols.** The single-protocol cases are the exception. The moment you have *another agent that itself uses tools* you need A2A (to reach the agent) + MCP (for the agent's tools) — the second row. A regulated workflow adds ACP for the audit trail on top of that. A transaction with an untrusted counterparty adds ANP for decentralized trust. Each protocol owns one axis: MCP owns the tool axis, A2A owns the agent axis, ACP owns the compliance axis, ANP owns the trust axis. They compose because they are *orthogonal* — none subsumes another.

**The design lesson.** Treating these as rivals ("should I use MCP *or* A2A?") is the wrong frame and leads to reimplementing one protocol's job inside another (an A2A integration that hand-rolls tool calls, or an MCP server that smuggles agent delegation through a fake tool). The right frame is a *stack*: identify every axis the request touches and layer the protocol that owns each. This is why every major framework now ships both MCP and A2A, and why enterprise stacks add ACP — production agent systems live at the intersection, not at a single point. The cost is operational complexity (more moving protocol layers to secure and monitor), which is the trade you accept for not rebuilding solved problems badly.
